\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Data Classification Schema
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The County shall classify all data into one (1) of four (4) levels based on the potential impact of unauthorized disclosure,
 modification,
 destruction,
 or loss of availability.
 Classification shall drive mandatory safeguards,
 handling restrictions,
 and access enforcement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\series bold
\lang english
6.2 Level 1 —
 Public
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Public information explicitly approved for unrestricted distribution.
 Unauthorized disclosure would reasonably result in no harm to the County.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Examples
\series default
:
 Published press releases,
 public meeting agendas,
 job postings,
 public website content.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Minimum Safeguards
\series default
:
 Integrity controls sufficient to prevent unauthorized modification or defacement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\series bold
\lang english
6.3 Level 2 —
 Internal Use
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Operational information intended for internal County business use.
 Disclosure may cause operational confusion,
 reputational harm,
 or unnecessary disruption but is not inherently sensitive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Examples
\series default
:
 Internal memos,
 internal directories,
 standard procedures,
 non-sensitive drafts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Minimum Safeguards
\series default
:
 Standard access controls (unique user authentication),
 standard backup,
 and retention per approved schedules.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Level 3 —
 Confidential
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Sensitive information that,
 if compromised,
 could negatively impact individual privacy,
 County finances,
 legal posture,
 or operational security.
 Access shall be limited to personnel with a validated business need-to-know.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Examples
\series default
:
 PII (as defined in NRS 603A),
 personnel records,
 vendor contracts containing non-public financial terms,
 draft budgets,
 privileged legal communications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Minimum Safeguards
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Access
\series default
:
 Role-based access control (RBAC) and least privilege enforcement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Encryption
\series default
:
 County-approved encryption at rest shall be required for mobile devices,
 portable storage,
 and systems storing Confidential data outside a County-controlled physically secure location.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Logging
\series default
:
 Systems storing Confidential information shall generate audit logs appropriate to the risk,
 and privileged access to such systems shall be logged in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.11"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Level 4 —
 Restricted
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Highly sensitive data protected by strict federal or state requirements.
 Unauthorized disclosure or modification could result in severe legal penalties,
 loss of program access,
 loss of funding,
 or public safety impacts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Examples
\series default
:
 Criminal Justice Information (CJI),
 Protected Health Information (PHI) where applicable,
 active investigative data,
 administrative credentials,
 cryptographic keys.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Minimum Safeguards
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Encryption
\series default
:
 Restricted data shall be protected using FIPS-validated cryptographic modules (FIPS 140-3,
 or FIPS 140-2 until September 21,
 2026) for data at rest and in transit,
 consistent with CJIS requirements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Access
\series default
:
 Multi-factor authentication (MFA) shall be required for access to Restricted data systems,
 Restricted data repositories,
 and administrative functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Exposure Controls
\series default
:
 Restricted data systems shall not be directly exposed to the public Internet without County-approved boundary protection and segmentation appropriate to the risk and consistent with CJIS requirements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Auditing
\series default
:
 The County shall capture and retain audit records for access,
 modification,
 and deletion events in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.11"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
,
 CJIS requirements for CJI,
 and mandatory Nevada retention requirements.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.6 Data Handling and Stewardship Principles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Classification Assignment and Security Attributes
\series default
:
 Data Owners shall assign the appropriate classification at creation or intake.
 The County shall associate classification as a security attribute where technically feasible to support access enforcement,
 handling rules,
 and auditability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Labeling and Marking
\series default
:
 Where technically feasible,
 digital documents and physical media containing Confidential or Restricted information shall be labeled with the assigned classification (e.g.,
 headers/footers,
 watermarking,
 media labels) to ensure personnel are aware of required handling and disclosure constraints.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Access Control and Need-to-Know
\series default
:
 Confidential and Restricted data shall be accessible only to authorized users with a validated business need-to-know.
 Access shall be enforced through approved identity and access management controls consistent with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.04"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 and 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.05"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 and shall be reviewed and adjusted when personnel roles change or upon termination of employment or contract.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Transmission Security
\series default
:
 Confidential and Restricted data shall not be transmitted over unprotected channels.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Restricted Data
\series default
:
 Shall be transmitted only using County-approved secure methods that enforce strong encryption in transit (e.g.,
 approved VPN,
 TLS 1.2 or higher,
 or other approved secure protocols consistent with CJIS requirements).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Email Restrictions
\series default
:
 Standard unencrypted email shall not be used to transmit Restricted data.
 If transmission is explicitly authorized for business necessity,
 the County shall use an approved encryption method or secure delivery mechanism authorized by the IT Director.
 Restricted CJI shall only be transmitted in accordance with the FBI CJIS Security Policy.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Authorized Storage Locations and Cloud Security Assurance
\series default
:
 County data shall be stored only in authorized repositories and systems approved by the IT Director.
 Personal cloud storage,
 personal email accounts,
 and unsanctioned collaboration tools are prohibited for County data.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Cloud Security Assurance
\series default
:
 Vendors or cloud service providers hosting Confidential or Restricted County data shall be evaluated and governed through the vendor governance process defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.13"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 Third-party authorizations (e.g.,
 FedRAMP,
 StateRAMP,
 SOC 2) may support due diligence but shall not be represented as automatically meeting CJIS Security Policy requirements or substituting for required CJIS agreements/addenda.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
CJI Cloud Requirements
\series default
:
 Systems storing or processing CJI in cloud environments shall meet all CJIS Security Policy requirements for encryption,
 access control,
 auditing,
 personnel security,
 and agreement/oversight obligations applicable to the service model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
CJI Data Sovereignty
\series default
:
 As an Elko County standard for CJIS risk control and audit defensibility,
 CJI shall only be stored or processed within the legal jurisdiction of an APB-member country and under the legal authority of an APB-member agency unless permitted by the CSA/CSO and approved in writing by the LASO,
 with all required CJIS governing approvals documented.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Storage,
 Media Control,
 and Disposal:
 Confidential and Restricted data shall be protected through secure storage controls and shall be destroyed or sanitized when no longer required,
 consistent with retention requirements and Policy 2.12,
 in a manner that renders the data unrecoverable prior to disposal,
 transfer,
 or reuse of the media.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.7 Reclassification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Data classification is not static.
 Data Owners shall review classifications annually,
 at minimum,
 and shall update classification when sensitivity,
 disclosure status,
 legal posture,
 or operational context changes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
CJI Reclassification Constraint
\series default
:
 Restricted CJI shall not be reclassified downward without written authorization from the IT Director (as LASO) and any additional CJIS authority required by governing agreements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.8 Data Inventory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director,
 in coordination with Department Heads,
 shall maintain a County Data Inventory that identifies:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Data categories and assigned classification levels.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Data Owner (Department Head) for each category.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Logical and physical storage locations (including approved cloud services).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Applicable retention requirements based on mandatory Nevada retention schedules and County directives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Data Inventory shall be reviewed and updated annually and following significant changes to systems,
 services,
 or regulatory obligations.
 The Data Inventory shall support the System Inventory maintained under Policy 1.12 and the Risk Register maintained under Policy 1.09.
\end_layout

